{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:11:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:11:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1633"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1633"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.38,0.03,0.02,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55330"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1633"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40858"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15622"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42356"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55330"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of sudden onset palpitations, dyspnoea, and dizziness. He denies any loss of consciousness. He has a recent history of an upper respiratory tract infection but is otherwise well, with no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears anxious. His pulse rate is irregular at approximately 120/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. A 12-lead ECG is performed. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrial fibrillation","Paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia","Right bundle branch block","Left bundle branch block","Wolff\u2013Parkinson\u2013White syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis ECG demonstrates the characteristic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E (AF) including an irregularly irregular rhythm, the absence of P waves, and narrow QRS complexes. AF often initially presents in a paroxysmal form, defined by self-termination within 7 days. In this case, the cause of AF is most likely related to the recent respiratory infection. Other causes of AF can be encapsulated in the mnemonic PIRATES: Pulmonary, Intrinsic, Rheumatic, Atrial myxoma, Thyroid, Emboli, Sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG also demonstrates Ashman phenomenon. This occurs as a result of \u0022long-short\u0022 coupling and occurs when a short RR interval is preceded by a relatively prolonged RR interval, resulting in an aberrantly conducted beat with right bundle branch block (RBBB) morphology. In this example, the Ashman beats are 1, 2, 3, 15, 16, and 17 of this strip. Ashman phenomenon is typically seen in atrial fibrillation but may occur with other supraventricular arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParoxysmal supraventricular tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E (PSVT) typically presents with a sudden onset of rapid, regular rhythm with a rate of 150-250 beats per minute. Unlike AF, PSVT has a regular rhythm and often shows retrograde P waves after the QRS complexes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight bundle branch block\u003C/strong\u003E (RBBB) is a conduction abnormality characterized by a widened QRS complex (\u003E120 ms) with a characteristic RSR\u0027 pattern in lead V1 and a wide S wave in leads I and V6. While some beats in this ECG show RBBB morphology due to Ashman phenomenon, the underlying rhythm is clearly AF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft bundle branch block\u003C/strong\u003E (LBBB) is also a conduction abnormality with a widened QRS complex (\u003E120 ms), but it shows a different pattern: broad, notched, or slurred R waves in leads I, aVL, V5, and V6, and QS or rS complexes in lead V1. This ECG does not show these features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWolff\u2013Parkinson\u2013White syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (WPW) is characterized by a short PR interval (\u003C120 ms), a widened QRS complex (\u003E110 ms), and a delta wave (slurred upstroke of the QRS complex). These features are not present in this ECG. While WPW can predispose to AF, the ECG would still show these characteristic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the irregularly irregular rhythm, absence of P waves, and predominantly narrow QRS complexes (with some aberrantly conducted beats due to Ashman phenomenon) are diagnostic of atrial fibrillation in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Atrial fibrillation has the following characteristic features on ECG: irregularly irregular rhythm, the absence of P waves and narrow QRS complexes","Ashman phenomenon in atrial fibrillation results in aberrantly conducted beats with RBBB morphology following a long-short RR interval sequence"],"references":["Iwasaki Y. Atrial fibrillation pathophysiology: implications for management. Circulation. 2011;124(20):2264-72."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40858"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1633"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"846"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/846"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8826f37f-30b8-4669-b7c2-97a670fc7eb1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8826f37f-30b8-4669-b7c2-97a670fc7eb1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":408}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40858"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T19:54:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T19:55:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1633"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55330"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"106","links":{"self":"https://